  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Bad idea -- the example IS a philosophical experiment",
    "content": "**Bad idea.** \n\nThe 道德仁义礼 passage is a philosophical experiment, as we established. Its function is not merely to illustrate a point that could be illustrated with any example -- it is to make the reader *undergo* the experience of seeing a metaphysical hierarchy constructed bottom-up from phenomena and then inverted. Swapping it for a Western example would mean constructing an entirely new philosophical experiment, with no guarantee it produces the same experiential effect.\n\nFurthermore, the passage demonstrates something the author explicitly values: that the framework applies across philosophical traditions. A Chinese example analyzed with a post-Kantian structural method is itself evidence for the cross-cultural reach of the framework. Replacing it with a Western example would make the collection look like Western philosophy applied to Western material -- losing precisely the cross-traditional dimension that makes it distinctive.\n\nThe translation apparatus (constitutive character, glosses, TNs) is manageable. The reader absorbs five terms in one passage and then moves on. That is a small cost for preserving both the philosophical experiment and the cross-cultural significance.\n"
  }
}
